00:00:20.650 --> 00:00:36.920
PROFESSOR: So today's topic
is liquid gas condensation

00:00:36.920 --> 00:00:40.690
and throughout this
course I have already

00:00:40.690 --> 00:00:43.710
mentioned two
different perspectives

00:00:43.710 --> 00:00:46.220
on the same
phenomenon, transition

00:00:46.220 --> 00:00:48.790
between liquid and gas.

00:00:48.790 --> 00:00:54.290
One perspective was when we
looked at the phase diagram

00:00:54.290 --> 00:00:56.360
even in the first
lecture I mentioned

00:00:56.360 --> 00:01:04.680
that if you look at
something like water

00:01:04.680 --> 00:01:06.800
as a function of
pressure and temperature

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:10.710
it can exist in three
different phases.

00:01:10.710 --> 00:01:14.800
There is the gas
phase, which you

00:01:14.800 --> 00:01:18.010
have at high temperatures
and low pressures.

00:01:18.010 --> 00:01:21.360
At low temperatures
and high pressures

00:01:21.360 --> 00:01:24.240
you have the liquid phase.

00:01:24.240 --> 00:01:31.960
And of course at
very low temperatures

00:01:31.960 --> 00:01:37.110
you also have the possibility
of the solid phase.

00:01:37.110 --> 00:01:39.920
And our concern
at some point was

00:01:39.920 --> 00:01:44.840
to think about the location of
the coexistence of the three

00:01:44.840 --> 00:01:52.230
phases of that was set as
the basis of the temperature,

00:01:52.230 --> 00:01:56.020
273.16.

00:01:56.020 --> 00:01:58.800
Actually what you're
going to focus now

00:01:58.800 --> 00:02:02.320
is not this part of
the phase diagram

00:02:02.320 --> 00:02:07.480
but the portion that consists
of the transition between liquid

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:10.449
and gas phases.

00:02:10.449 --> 00:02:14.150
And this coexistence
line actually

00:02:14.150 --> 00:02:20.190
terminates at what is called
the critical point that we will

00:02:20.190 --> 00:02:25.080
talk about more today at the
particular value of Tc and Pc.

00:02:28.930 --> 00:02:32.230
An equivalent perspective
that we have looked at that

00:02:32.230 --> 00:02:35.420
and I just want to make sure
that you have both of these

00:02:35.420 --> 00:02:38.940
in mind and know the
relationship between them

00:02:38.940 --> 00:02:41.840
is to look at isotherms.

00:02:41.840 --> 00:02:45.560
Basically we also
looked at cases

00:02:45.560 --> 00:02:51.200
where we looked at isotherms
of pressure versus volume.

00:02:51.200 --> 00:02:56.540
And this statement was that
if we look at the system

00:02:56.540 --> 00:03:04.160
at high enough temperatures and
low enough pressures so let's

00:03:04.160 --> 00:03:10.220
say pick this temperature and
scan along a line such as this,

00:03:10.220 --> 00:03:13.370
it would be equivalent
over here to have

00:03:13.370 --> 00:03:19.300
some kind of an isotherm that is
kind of potentially a distorted

00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:24.090
version of an ideal
gas hyperbola.

00:03:24.090 --> 00:03:30.640
Now if we were to look
at another isotherm

00:03:30.640 --> 00:03:35.080
that corresponds to
this scan over here then

00:03:35.080 --> 00:03:39.190
what would happen is
that it will cross

00:03:39.190 --> 00:03:42.360
this line of the
coexistence, part of it

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:44.300
would fall in the
liquid phase, part of it

00:03:44.300 --> 00:03:46.400
would fall in the gas phase.

00:03:46.400 --> 00:03:49.720
And we draw the
corresponding isotherm,

00:03:49.720 --> 00:03:51.750
it would look
something like this.

00:03:51.750 --> 00:03:54.110
There would be a
portion that would

00:03:54.110 --> 00:03:57.650
correspond to being
in the liquid.

00:03:57.650 --> 00:03:59.190
There would be a
portion that would

00:03:59.190 --> 00:04:00.875
correspond to being in the gas.

00:04:04.520 --> 00:04:09.460
And this line, this point
where you hit this line

00:04:09.460 --> 00:04:14.450
would correspond
to the coexistence.

00:04:14.450 --> 00:04:20.610
Essentially you could change
the volume of a container

00:04:20.610 --> 00:04:27.450
and at high volumes, you
would start with entirety gas.

00:04:27.450 --> 00:04:30.070
At the same pressure
and temperature

00:04:30.070 --> 00:04:33.440
you could squeeze it
and some of the gas

00:04:33.440 --> 00:04:36.590
would get converted
to liquid and you

00:04:36.590 --> 00:04:39.580
would have a coexistence
of gas and liquid

00:04:39.580 --> 00:04:42.880
until you squeezed it
sufficiently, still maintaining

00:04:42.880 --> 00:04:45.310
the same pressure
and temperature

00:04:45.310 --> 00:04:47.970
until your container
was fully liquid.

00:04:47.970 --> 00:04:51.650
So that's a different
type of isotherm.

00:04:51.650 --> 00:04:55.110
And what we discussed
was that basically there

00:04:55.110 --> 00:05:03.410
is a coexistence
boundary that separates

00:05:03.410 --> 00:05:07.470
the first and the second
types of isotherms.

00:05:07.470 --> 00:05:14.380
And presumably in between
there is some trajectory

00:05:14.380 --> 00:05:17.570
that would correspond to
basically being exactly

00:05:17.570 --> 00:05:22.138
at the boundary and it would
look something like this.

00:05:22.138 --> 00:05:27.440
This would be the trajectory
that you would have at Tc.

00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:29.930
The location Pc is
the same, of course,

00:05:29.930 --> 00:05:32.660
so basically I
can carry this out

00:05:32.660 --> 00:05:36.970
so there is the same Pc
that would occur here.

00:05:36.970 --> 00:05:41.480
And there would be
some particular Vc

00:05:41.480 --> 00:05:46.240
but that depends on the amount
of material that I have.

00:05:46.240 --> 00:05:48.240
OK?

00:05:48.240 --> 00:05:55.260
So we are going to try to
understand what is happening

00:05:55.260 --> 00:06:00.750
here and in particular
we note that suddenly we

00:06:00.750 --> 00:06:04.900
have to deal with cases
where there are singularities

00:06:04.900 --> 00:06:09.110
in our thermodynamic parameters.

00:06:09.110 --> 00:06:11.310
There's some
thermodynamic parameter

00:06:11.310 --> 00:06:16.000
that I'm scanning as I
go across the system.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:18.300
It will not be
varying continuously.

00:06:18.300 --> 00:06:21.440
It has these kinds of
discontinuities in it.

00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:25.830
And how did discontinuities
appear and how can

00:06:25.830 --> 00:06:28.660
we account for these
phase transitions

00:06:28.660 --> 00:06:31.610
given the formalisms
that we have developed

00:06:31.610 --> 00:06:35.080
for studying
thermodynamic functions.

00:06:35.080 --> 00:06:38.460
And in particular
let's, for example,

00:06:38.460 --> 00:06:45.000
start with the canonical
prescription where I state,

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:52.210
let's say that I have volume
and temperature of a fixed

00:06:52.210 --> 00:06:55.980
number of particles and
I want to figure out

00:06:55.980 --> 00:06:59.410
thermodynamic properties
in this perspective.

00:06:59.410 --> 00:07:03.020
What I need to calculate
is a partition function

00:07:03.020 --> 00:07:06.460
and we've seen that the
partition function is obtained

00:07:06.460 --> 00:07:12.140
by integrating over all degrees
of freedom which are basically

00:07:12.140 --> 00:07:15.720
the coordinates and momentum
of particles that make up

00:07:15.720 --> 00:07:19.030
this gas so I have
to do d cubed p i,

00:07:19.030 --> 00:07:26.530
d cubed q i, divide by h cubed,
divide by n factorial because

00:07:26.530 --> 00:07:30.710
of the way that we've been
looking at things, of energy

00:07:30.710 --> 00:07:36.030
so I have e to the minus
beta h that has a part that

00:07:36.030 --> 00:07:43.670
is from the kinetic energy which
I can integrate immediately.

00:07:43.670 --> 00:07:47.920
And then it has a part that
is from the potential energy

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:50.490
of the interactions among
all of these particles.

00:07:55.581 --> 00:07:57.980
OK?

00:07:57.980 --> 00:08:03.610
So somehow if I could
do these integrations--

00:08:03.610 --> 00:08:06.280
we already did them for
an ideal gas and nothing

00:08:06.280 --> 00:08:08.050
special happened
but presumably if I

00:08:08.050 --> 00:08:12.950
can do that for the case of
an interacting gas, buried

00:08:12.950 --> 00:08:18.660
within it would be the
properties of this phase

00:08:18.660 --> 00:08:21.950
transition and the
singularities, et cetera.

00:08:21.950 --> 00:08:24.900
Question is how
does that happen?

00:08:24.900 --> 00:08:27.710
So last time we tried
to do shortcuts.

00:08:27.710 --> 00:08:31.520
We started with calculating a
first derivative calculation

00:08:31.520 --> 00:08:35.500
in this potential and
then try to guess things

00:08:35.500 --> 00:08:38.580
and maybe that was
not so satisfactory.

00:08:38.580 --> 00:08:41.309
So today we'll take
another approach

00:08:41.309 --> 00:08:44.290
to calculating this
partition function where

00:08:44.290 --> 00:08:46.980
the approximations and
assumptions are more

00:08:46.980 --> 00:08:54.290
clearly stated and we
can see what happens.

00:08:54.290 --> 00:08:57.480
So I want to calculate
this partition function.

00:08:57.480 --> 00:08:58.440
OK?

00:08:58.440 --> 00:09:00.540
So part of that
partition function

00:09:00.540 --> 00:09:06.030
that depends on the momentum I
can very easily take care of.

00:09:06.030 --> 00:09:09.890
That gives me these
factors of 1 over lambda.

00:09:09.890 --> 00:09:18.660
Again as usual my lambda
is h over 2 pi m k T

00:09:18.660 --> 00:09:22.740
and then I have to do
the integrations over all

00:09:22.740 --> 00:09:29.410
of the coordinates, all of
these coordinate integrations

00:09:29.410 --> 00:09:32.160
and the potential that I'm
going to be thinking about,

00:09:32.160 --> 00:09:35.780
so again in my U
will be something

00:09:35.780 --> 00:09:41.640
like sum over pairs
V of q i minus q j,

00:09:41.640 --> 00:09:46.450
where the typical form of this V
as a function of the separation

00:09:46.450 --> 00:09:50.830
that I'm going to
look at has presumably

00:09:50.830 --> 00:09:55.360
a part that is hard-core
and a part that is attract.

00:09:55.360 --> 00:09:58.200
Something like this.

00:09:58.200 --> 00:09:59.560
OK?

00:09:59.560 --> 00:10:04.900
So given that potential what
are the kinds of configurations

00:10:04.900 --> 00:10:06.835
I expect to happen in my system?

00:10:06.835 --> 00:10:08.840
Well, let's see.

00:10:08.840 --> 00:10:11.640
Let's try to make a diagram.

00:10:11.640 --> 00:10:17.150
I have a huge number of
particles that don't come very

00:10:17.150 --> 00:10:20.020
close to each other, there's
a hard-core repulsion,

00:10:20.020 --> 00:10:24.200
so maybe I can think of them
as having some kind of a size--

00:10:24.200 --> 00:10:28.870
marbles, et cetera, and they are
distributed so that they cannot

00:10:28.870 --> 00:10:29.950
come close to each other.

00:10:33.390 --> 00:10:37.030
More than that are
zero and then I

00:10:37.030 --> 00:10:40.480
have to sum over all
configurations that

00:10:40.480 --> 00:10:44.280
are compatible where they
are not crossing each other

00:10:44.280 --> 00:10:46.550
and calculate e to
the minus beta u.

00:10:50.790 --> 00:10:55.860
So let's try to do some kind
of an approximation to this u.

00:10:55.860 --> 00:11:01.030
I claim that I can write this
U as follows- I can write it

00:11:01.030 --> 00:11:04.840
as one-half, basically
this i less than j,

00:11:04.840 --> 00:11:08.370
I can write as one-half
all i not equal to j,

00:11:08.370 --> 00:11:11.310
so that's where the
one-half comes from.

00:11:11.310 --> 00:11:14.090
I will write it as one-half
but not in this form,

00:11:14.090 --> 00:11:20.170
as an integral d cubed
r d cubed r prime n of r

00:11:20.170 --> 00:11:28.520
n of r prime v of r minus
r prime where n of r

00:11:28.520 --> 00:11:39.125
is sum over all particles asking
whether they are at location r.

00:11:42.100 --> 00:11:47.450
So I can pick some
particle opposition here--

00:11:47.450 --> 00:11:54.030
let's call it r-- ask whether or
not there is a particle there,

00:11:54.030 --> 00:11:58.270
construct the density by
summing over everywhere.

00:11:58.270 --> 00:12:00.450
You can convince
yourself that if I

00:12:00.450 --> 00:12:03.960
were to substitute
this back over here,

00:12:03.960 --> 00:12:07.490
the integrals over r
and r prime can be done

00:12:07.490 --> 00:12:11.880
and they sit r and r prime
respectively to sum q i and q j

00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:15.596
and I will get back the
sum that I had before.

00:12:15.596 --> 00:12:16.095
OK?

00:12:19.150 --> 00:12:20.810
So what is that thing doing?

00:12:20.810 --> 00:12:25.620
Essentially it says
pick some point, r,

00:12:25.620 --> 00:12:30.530
and then look at some
other point, r prime,

00:12:30.530 --> 00:12:33.310
ask whether there are
particles in that point

00:12:33.310 --> 00:12:37.960
and then sum over all pairs
of points r and r prime.

00:12:37.960 --> 00:12:39.790
So I changed my perspective.

00:12:39.790 --> 00:12:44.400
Rather than calculating the
energy by looking at particles,

00:12:44.400 --> 00:12:47.920
I essentially look
at parts of space,

00:12:47.920 --> 00:12:51.940
ask how many
particles there are.

00:12:51.940 --> 00:12:54.600
Well, it kind of makes
sense if I coarse-grained

00:12:54.600 --> 00:12:57.690
this a little bit that
the density should

00:12:57.690 --> 00:13:01.460
be more or less the same
in every single box.

00:13:01.460 --> 00:13:10.050
So I make the assumption
of uniform density--

00:13:10.050 --> 00:13:12.210
I shouldn't say
assumption, let's

00:13:12.210 --> 00:13:21.680
call it an approximation of
uniform density in which I

00:13:21.680 --> 00:13:24.630
replace this n of r
by it's average value

00:13:24.630 --> 00:13:29.752
which is the number of
particles per [INAUDIBLE].

00:13:29.752 --> 00:13:31.730
OK?

00:13:31.730 --> 00:13:38.230
Then my U-- I will
take the n's outside.

00:13:38.230 --> 00:13:42.830
I will have one-half n
squared integral d cubed

00:13:42.830 --> 00:13:46.870
r d cubed r prime v
of r minus r prime.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:54.650
Again it really is a function
of the relative distance

00:13:54.650 --> 00:13:57.950
so I can integrate
over the center of mass

00:13:57.950 --> 00:14:00.150
if you like to get
one factor of volumes

00:14:00.150 --> 00:14:04.380
so I have one n
squared V and then

00:14:04.380 --> 00:14:06.770
I have an integral
over the relative

00:14:06.770 --> 00:14:10.760
coordinate d cubed r-- let's
write it as 4 pi r squared d

00:14:10.760 --> 00:14:16.150
r, the potential as a
function of separation.

00:14:16.150 --> 00:14:20.340
Now the only configurations
that are possible

00:14:20.340 --> 00:14:27.370
are ones that don't really
come closer than wherever

00:14:27.370 --> 00:14:30.790
the particles are on
top of each other,

00:14:30.790 --> 00:14:37.430
so really there is some kind
of a minimum value over here.

00:14:37.430 --> 00:14:40.440
The maximum value you could
say is the size of the box

00:14:40.440 --> 00:14:43.650
but the typical range of
potentials that we are thinking

00:14:43.650 --> 00:14:47.000
is much, much less than
the size of the box.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:48.940
So for all intents
and purposes I

00:14:48.940 --> 00:14:54.790
can set the value of the other
part of the thing to infinity.

00:14:54.790 --> 00:15:02.700
So what I'm doing is essentially
I'm integrating this portion

00:15:02.700 --> 00:15:09.395
and I can call the result
of doing that to be minus u.

00:15:09.395 --> 00:15:10.710
Why minus?

00:15:10.710 --> 00:15:13.620
Because it's clearly
the attractive portion

00:15:13.620 --> 00:15:16.480
in this picture I'm integrating.

00:15:16.480 --> 00:15:20.420
And you can convince yourself
that if I use the potential

00:15:20.420 --> 00:15:23.280
that I had before-- yes,
the last time around it

00:15:23.280 --> 00:15:27.715
was minus u 0 r 0 over
r to the sixth power,

00:15:27.715 --> 00:15:35.400
but this u is actually the
omega that I was using times u 0

00:15:35.400 --> 00:15:38.990
but I will keep it as
u to sort of indicate

00:15:38.990 --> 00:15:41.560
that it could be a
more general potential.

00:15:41.560 --> 00:15:45.210
But the specific potential that
we were working with last time

00:15:45.210 --> 00:15:47.660
to calculate the second
visual coefficient

00:15:47.660 --> 00:15:48.910
would correspond to that.

00:15:48.910 --> 00:15:53.550
So essentially I claim
that the configurations

00:15:53.550 --> 00:15:56.720
that I'm interested
will give a contribution

00:15:56.720 --> 00:16:00.120
to the energy which is
minus whatever this u 0--

00:16:00.120 --> 00:16:03.770
u is n squared V divided by 2.

00:16:07.800 --> 00:16:11.350
Now clearly not
all configuration

00:16:11.350 --> 00:16:12.610
has the same energy.

00:16:12.610 --> 00:16:14.650
I mean that's the
whole thing, I have

00:16:14.650 --> 00:16:17.880
to really integrate
overall configurations.

00:16:17.880 --> 00:16:21.050
I've sort of looked at
an average contribution.

00:16:21.050 --> 00:16:23.930
There will be configurations
where the particles are

00:16:23.930 --> 00:16:26.570
more bunched or separate,
differently arranged,

00:16:26.570 --> 00:16:29.480
et cetera, and
energy would vary.

00:16:29.480 --> 00:16:31.780
But I expect that
most of the time--

00:16:31.780 --> 00:16:34.470
I see something like
a gas in this room,

00:16:34.470 --> 00:16:36.550
there is a uniform
density typically.

00:16:36.550 --> 00:16:38.870
The fluctuations in
density I can ignore

00:16:38.870 --> 00:16:41.560
and I will have a
contribution such as this.

00:16:41.560 --> 00:16:48.750
So this factor I will replace
by what I have over here.

00:16:48.750 --> 00:16:52.070
What I have over here will
give me e to the minus

00:16:52.070 --> 00:16:58.090
beta u density squared actually
I can write as N squared

00:16:58.090 --> 00:17:05.179
over V squared, one of V's
cancel here, I have 2 V. OK?

00:17:08.680 --> 00:17:12.520
So that's the typical value of
this quantity but now I have

00:17:12.520 --> 00:17:16.930
to do the integrations
over all of the q's.

00:17:16.930 --> 00:17:17.430
Yes?

00:17:17.430 --> 00:17:19.550
AUDIENCE: In terms of the
approximation you made--

00:17:19.550 --> 00:17:20.175
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:17:20.175 --> 00:17:23.020
AUDIENCE: --the implications are
that if you have a more complex

00:17:23.020 --> 00:17:23.535
potential--

00:17:23.535 --> 00:17:24.160
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:17:24.160 --> 00:17:26.618
AUDIENCE: --you'll get into
trouble with for a given sample

00:17:26.618 --> 00:17:30.130
size, it will be less accurate.

00:17:30.130 --> 00:17:31.702
would you agree with that?

00:17:31.702 --> 00:17:34.035
PROFESSOR: What do you mean
by a more complex potential?

00:17:34.035 --> 00:17:35.250
Until you tell me, I can't--

00:17:35.250 --> 00:17:38.370
AUDIENCE: I mean I, guess,
and usually-- I mean,

00:17:38.370 --> 00:17:40.362
I guess if you had like
multi-body or maybe

00:17:40.362 --> 00:17:41.830
the cell group.

00:17:41.830 --> 00:17:42.550
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:17:42.550 --> 00:17:46.850
So certainly what I have assumed
here is a two-body potential.

00:17:46.850 --> 00:17:49.220
If I had a three-body
potential then I

00:17:49.220 --> 00:17:51.930
would have a term that
would be density cubed, yes.

00:17:51.930 --> 00:17:54.530
AUDIENCE: But then you would--
my point is that-- and maybe

00:17:54.530 --> 00:17:58.870
it's not a place to question--
for a given sample size,

00:17:58.870 --> 00:18:01.420
I would imagine there's some
relation between how small

00:18:01.420 --> 00:18:04.440
it can be and the complexity
of the potential when you make

00:18:04.440 --> 00:18:07.547
this uniform density assumption.

00:18:07.547 --> 00:18:08.130
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:18:08.130 --> 00:18:12.630
We are always evaluating things
in the thermodynamic limit,

00:18:12.630 --> 00:18:16.410
so ultimately I'm always
interested in m and v going

00:18:16.410 --> 00:18:21.310
to infinity, while the
ratio of n over v is fixed.

00:18:21.310 --> 00:18:22.310
OK?

00:18:22.310 --> 00:18:27.060
So things-- there are certainly
problems associated with let's

00:18:27.060 --> 00:18:31.220
say extending the range of
this integration to infinity.

00:18:31.220 --> 00:18:34.390
We essentially are
not worrying about

00:18:34.390 --> 00:18:36.840
the walls of the
container, et cetera.

00:18:36.840 --> 00:18:39.970
All of those effects
are proportional to area

00:18:39.970 --> 00:18:43.540
and in the thermodynamic limit,
the ratio of area to volume

00:18:43.540 --> 00:18:44.530
goes to zero.

00:18:44.530 --> 00:18:46.150
I can ignore that.

00:18:46.150 --> 00:18:49.070
If I bring things to
become smaller and smaller,

00:18:49.070 --> 00:18:51.180
then I need to worry
about a lot of things,

00:18:51.180 --> 00:18:54.730
like do particles absorb
on surfaces, et cetera.

00:18:54.730 --> 00:18:56.490
I don't want to do that.

00:18:56.490 --> 00:18:58.780
But if you are worrying
about complexity

00:18:58.780 --> 00:19:03.430
of the potential such as I
assume things to be radially

00:19:03.430 --> 00:19:05.610
symmetric, you
say, well actually

00:19:05.610 --> 00:19:08.310
if I think about
oxygen molecules,

00:19:08.310 --> 00:19:09.500
they are not vertical.

00:19:09.500 --> 00:19:12.380
They have a dipole-dipole
interactions potentially,

00:19:12.380 --> 00:19:13.190
et cetera.

00:19:13.190 --> 00:19:17.610
All of those you can take care
of by doing this integral more

00:19:17.610 --> 00:19:18.670
carefully.

00:19:18.670 --> 00:19:22.900
Ultimately the value of your
parameter u will be different.

00:19:22.900 --> 00:19:25.930
AUDIENCE: But I guess what I'm
getting at is you deviate from

00:19:25.930 --> 00:19:29.210
the-- if you're doing it-- if
we're back when computers are

00:19:29.210 --> 00:19:31.126
not as fast and you can
essentially approach

00:19:31.126 --> 00:19:33.659
the thermodynamic limit and
you're doing a simulation

00:19:33.659 --> 00:19:35.200
and you want to use
these as a tool--

00:19:35.200 --> 00:19:36.282
PROFESSOR: Mm-hmm?

00:19:36.282 --> 00:19:38.490
AUDIENCE: --then you get
into those questions, right?

00:19:38.490 --> 00:19:39.115
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:19:39.115 --> 00:19:42.420
AUDIENCE: But this
framework should still work?

00:19:42.420 --> 00:19:43.100
PROFESSOR: No.

00:19:43.100 --> 00:19:46.170
This framework is
an approximation

00:19:46.170 --> 00:19:49.500
intended to answer the
following question--

00:19:49.500 --> 00:19:53.630
how is it possible that
singularities can emerge?

00:19:53.630 --> 00:19:56.180
And we will see
shortly that the origin

00:19:56.180 --> 00:19:58.430
of the emergence
of singularities

00:19:58.430 --> 00:20:01.130
is precisely this.

00:20:01.130 --> 00:20:05.610
And if I don't have that, then
I don't have singularities.

00:20:05.610 --> 00:20:08.320
So truly when you do
a computer simulation

00:20:08.320 --> 00:20:13.280
with 10 million particles, you
will not see the singularity.

00:20:13.280 --> 00:20:16.530
It emerges only in the
thermodynamic limit

00:20:16.530 --> 00:20:21.340
and my point here is to sort
of start from that limit.

00:20:21.340 --> 00:20:23.690
Once we understand
that limit, then maybe

00:20:23.690 --> 00:20:25.650
we can better
answer your question

00:20:25.650 --> 00:20:27.400
about limitations of
computer simulations.

00:20:31.580 --> 00:20:32.080
OK?

00:20:35.950 --> 00:20:39.260
So I've said that there's
basically configurations

00:20:39.260 --> 00:20:42.350
that typically give
the [INAUDIBLE].

00:20:42.350 --> 00:20:43.840
But how many configurations?

00:20:43.840 --> 00:20:47.590
I can certainly move
these particles around.

00:20:47.590 --> 00:20:52.650
And therefore I have to see what
the value of these integrations

00:20:52.650 --> 00:20:54.500
are.

00:20:54.500 --> 00:20:55.860
OK?

00:20:55.860 --> 00:21:00.980
So I will do so, as follows--
I will say that the first

00:21:00.980 --> 00:21:03.940
particle, if there
was nobody else--

00:21:03.940 --> 00:21:08.040
so I have to do this
integration over q 1, q 2, q 3,

00:21:08.040 --> 00:21:11.900
and I have some constraints in
the space that the q's cannot

00:21:11.900 --> 00:21:15.440
come closer to each
other than this distance.

00:21:15.440 --> 00:21:18.730
So what I'm going to
try to calculate now

00:21:18.730 --> 00:21:22.680
is how this factor of v to the
n that you would have normally

00:21:22.680 --> 00:21:27.510
put here for ideal
gases gets modified.

00:21:27.510 --> 00:21:30.410
Well I say that the first
particle that I put in the box

00:21:30.410 --> 00:21:33.100
can explore the entire space.

00:21:33.100 --> 00:21:37.030
If I had two particles,
the second particle

00:21:37.030 --> 00:21:39.640
could explore everything
except the region that

00:21:39.640 --> 00:21:43.670
is excluded by the
first particle.

00:21:43.670 --> 00:21:46.080
The second particle
that I put in

00:21:46.080 --> 00:21:49.860
can explore the space
minus the region that

00:21:49.860 --> 00:21:53.220
is excluded by the
first two particles.

00:21:53.220 --> 00:21:59.890
And the last, the end
particle, the space

00:21:59.890 --> 00:22:02.970
except the region
that is excluded

00:22:02.970 --> 00:22:05.340
by the first n minus 1.

00:22:05.340 --> 00:22:07.980
This is an approximation, right?

00:22:07.980 --> 00:22:12.650
So if I have three
particles, the space

00:22:12.650 --> 00:22:15.430
that is excluded for
the third particle

00:22:15.430 --> 00:22:18.840
can be more than this
if the two particles

00:22:18.840 --> 00:22:20.430
are kind of close to each other.

00:22:20.430 --> 00:22:22.030
If you have two
billiard balls that

00:22:22.030 --> 00:22:25.490
are kind of close to each
other the region between them

00:22:25.490 --> 00:22:28.700
is also excluded for
the first particle.

00:22:28.700 --> 00:22:33.680
We are throwing that out and
one can show that that is really

00:22:33.680 --> 00:22:35.610
throwing out things
that are higher

00:22:35.610 --> 00:22:40.010
order in the ratio of omega
over V So if you're right,

00:22:40.010 --> 00:22:44.930
this is really an
expansion in omega over V

00:22:44.930 --> 00:22:47.660
and I have calculated
things correctly

00:22:47.660 --> 00:22:50.040
to order of omega over V.

00:22:50.040 --> 00:22:53.910
And if I am consistent
with that and I multiply

00:22:53.910 --> 00:22:58.840
all of these things together,
the first term is V to the N

00:22:58.840 --> 00:23:05.600
and then I have 1 minus omega
plus 2 omega plus all the way

00:23:05.600 --> 00:23:12.940
to N minus 1 omega which then
basically sums out to 1 plus 2

00:23:12.940 --> 00:23:18.590
plus 3 all the way to N minus
1, which is N minus 1 over 2

00:23:18.590 --> 00:23:20.215
in the large N limit.

00:23:20.215 --> 00:23:23.786
It's the same thing
as N squared over 2

00:23:23.786 --> 00:23:29.750
and this whole thing is
raised to the power-- OK

00:23:29.750 --> 00:23:35.290
this whole thing I can
approximate by V minus N

00:23:35.290 --> 00:23:36.865
omega over 2 squared.

00:23:39.660 --> 00:23:41.300
There are various
ways of seeing this.

00:23:41.300 --> 00:23:46.320
I mean one way of seeing this
is to pair things one from one

00:23:46.320 --> 00:23:50.430
end and one from the
other end and then

00:23:50.430 --> 00:23:53.040
multiply them together.

00:23:53.040 --> 00:23:54.590
When you multiply
them you will have

00:23:54.590 --> 00:23:58.450
a term that would go be
V squared, a term that

00:23:58.450 --> 00:24:00.780
would be proportionate
to V omega

00:24:00.780 --> 00:24:04.520
and would be the sum of
the coefficients of omega

00:24:04.520 --> 00:24:06.530
from the two.

00:24:06.530 --> 00:24:10.220
And you can see that
if I pick, say, alpha

00:24:10.220 --> 00:24:12.640
term from this
side N minus alpha

00:24:12.640 --> 00:24:14.730
minus one term from
the other side,

00:24:14.730 --> 00:24:20.560
add them up, the alphas
cancel out, N and N minus 1

00:24:20.560 --> 00:24:24.150
are roughly the same, so
basically the square of two

00:24:24.150 --> 00:24:31.190
of them is the same as
the square of V minus N

00:24:31.190 --> 00:24:33.850
omega over 2.

00:24:33.850 --> 00:24:38.764
And then I can repeat that
for all pairs and I get this.

00:24:38.764 --> 00:24:39.263
Sorry.

00:24:42.970 --> 00:24:47.650
So the statement is that
the effect of the excluded

00:24:47.650 --> 00:24:57.000
volumes since it is joint
effect of mutually excluding

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:01.810
each other is that V to the
N that I have for ideal gas,

00:25:01.810 --> 00:25:04.950
each one of them can go
over the entire place,

00:25:04.950 --> 00:25:10.450
gets replaced by V minus
something to the power of N

00:25:10.450 --> 00:25:14.240
and that something
is N omega over 2.

00:25:17.810 --> 00:25:20.120
Plus higher orders
in powers of omega.

00:25:23.228 --> 00:25:23.728
OK?

00:25:28.520 --> 00:25:33.630
So I will call this a
mean field estimate.

00:25:39.900 --> 00:25:44.300
Really, it's an average
density estimate

00:25:44.300 --> 00:25:46.840
but this kind of
approximation is typically

00:25:46.840 --> 00:25:50.890
done for magnetic systems
and in that context

00:25:50.890 --> 00:25:54.840
the name of mean
field has stuck.

00:25:54.840 --> 00:26:00.850
And the ultimate result is that
my estimation for the partition

00:26:00.850 --> 00:26:09.210
function is 1 over
N factorial lambda

00:26:09.210 --> 00:26:14.660
to the power of 3 N V
minus N omega over 2

00:26:14.660 --> 00:26:20.370
raised to the power of N
because of the excluded volume

00:26:20.370 --> 00:26:22.960
and because of the Boltzmann
weight of the attraction

00:26:22.960 --> 00:26:25.070
between particles
I have a term which

00:26:25.070 --> 00:26:30.620
is e to the minus beta
U N squared over 2V.

00:26:37.480 --> 00:26:40.420
OK?

00:26:40.420 --> 00:26:44.740
So the approximations
are clear on what

00:26:44.740 --> 00:26:50.765
set of assumptions I get this
estimate for the partition

00:26:50.765 --> 00:26:53.450
function.

00:26:53.450 --> 00:26:55.730
Once I have the
partition function,

00:26:55.730 --> 00:27:00.060
I can calculate the
pressure because log z is

00:27:00.060 --> 00:27:01.890
going to be related
to free energy,

00:27:01.890 --> 00:27:05.500
the derivative of the free
energy respect to volume

00:27:05.500 --> 00:27:09.450
will give me the pressure,
and you can ultimately

00:27:09.450 --> 00:27:14.410
check that the formula
is that beta P is the log

00:27:14.410 --> 00:27:20.720
Z by d V. That's
the correct formula.

00:27:20.720 --> 00:27:24.490
And because we are doing this
in the canonical formalism

00:27:24.490 --> 00:27:27.490
that I emphasized
over here, let's

00:27:27.490 --> 00:27:31.080
call this P that we get through
this process beta P canonical.

00:27:33.625 --> 00:27:34.970
OK?

00:27:34.970 --> 00:27:40.060
So when I take log z,
there's a bunch of terms

00:27:40.060 --> 00:27:41.990
and I don't really
care about because they

00:27:41.990 --> 00:27:44.810
don't have V dependence
from N factorial lambda

00:27:44.810 --> 00:27:48.830
to the power of 3N,
but I have N times log

00:27:48.830 --> 00:27:52.260
of V minus N omega over 2.

00:27:52.260 --> 00:27:54.830
So that has V dependence.

00:27:54.830 --> 00:27:59.120
Take the derivative of log
of V minus N omega over 2,

00:27:59.120 --> 00:28:00.580
what do I get?

00:28:00.580 --> 00:28:03.760
I get V minus N omega over 2.

00:28:07.220 --> 00:28:10.000
The other theorem
when I take the log

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:15.020
I have a minus beta
U N squared over 2 V

00:28:15.020 --> 00:28:17.160
so then I take a
derivative of this 1

00:28:17.160 --> 00:28:20.480
over V. I will
get minus 1 over V

00:28:20.480 --> 00:28:23.500
squared so I have
a term here which

00:28:23.500 --> 00:28:33.090
is beta U over 2 N
squared over V squared.

00:28:37.930 --> 00:28:39.380
OK?

00:28:39.380 --> 00:28:41.930
Let's multiply by
k T so that we have

00:28:41.930 --> 00:28:47.220
the formula for P canonical.

00:28:47.220 --> 00:28:56.940
P canonical is then N k
T V minus N omega over 2

00:28:56.940 --> 00:29:02.750
and then I have-- I think I made
a sign over here-- yes the sign

00:29:02.750 --> 00:29:06.880
error that I made
is as follows-- note

00:29:06.880 --> 00:29:11.350
that the potential is attractive
so I have a minus U here.

00:29:11.350 --> 00:29:15.820
So when I exponentiate
that, it becomes a plus here

00:29:15.820 --> 00:29:20.260
and will be a plus
here and therefore I

00:29:20.260 --> 00:29:27.250
will have a minus here
and I will have a minus U

00:29:27.250 --> 00:29:32.740
over 2 times the
density squared.

00:29:32.740 --> 00:29:34.720
OK?

00:29:34.720 --> 00:29:36.600
So what did we arrive at?

00:29:36.600 --> 00:29:39.042
We arrived at the van
der Waals equation.

00:29:44.494 --> 00:29:44.994
OK?

00:29:47.970 --> 00:29:53.330
So we discussed
already last time

00:29:53.330 --> 00:30:00.030
around that if I now look
at the isotherms pressure

00:30:00.030 --> 00:30:02.970
volume at different
temperatures,

00:30:02.970 --> 00:30:05.980
at high temperatures
I have no problem.

00:30:05.980 --> 00:30:10.500
I will get things that look
reasonable except if I have

00:30:10.500 --> 00:30:17.220
to terminate at something that
is related to this excluded

00:30:17.220 --> 00:30:22.500
volume, whereas if I go to
low temperatures, what happens

00:30:22.500 --> 00:30:25.910
is that the kind of
isotherms that I get

00:30:25.910 --> 00:30:31.630
have a structure which
is kind of like this

00:30:31.630 --> 00:30:38.350
and incorporates a region
which violates everything

00:30:38.350 --> 00:30:40.630
that we know about
thermodynamics,

00:30:40.630 --> 00:30:43.880
is not stable, et cetera.

00:30:43.880 --> 00:30:46.420
OK?

00:30:46.420 --> 00:30:48.310
So what happened here?

00:30:52.230 --> 00:30:53.920
I did a calculation.

00:30:53.920 --> 00:30:58.000
You can see every step of
the calculation over there.

00:30:58.000 --> 00:30:59.370
Why does it give me nonsense?

00:31:07.350 --> 00:31:09.500
Everything that you need
