01:01:22.770 --> 01:01:27.990
are for the van der Waals or
other approximate equation

01:01:27.990 --> 01:01:29.620
of state such as
the one that you

01:01:29.620 --> 01:01:32.310
will encounter in the problems.

01:01:32.310 --> 01:01:34.430
So let's stick with
the van der Waals

01:01:34.430 --> 01:01:46.290
so the van der Waals equation
is that my P is-- actually

01:01:46.290 --> 01:01:55.400
let's divide by N so it
would be volume per particle

01:01:55.400 --> 01:02:00.920
so I have introduced V to be
the volume per particle which

01:02:00.920 --> 01:02:03.670
is the inverse of the
density, if you like,

01:02:03.670 --> 01:02:05.900
so that is intensive.

01:02:05.900 --> 01:02:09.100
V minus-- there's
some excluded volume,

01:02:09.100 --> 01:02:11.420
let's call it
through the volume b

01:02:11.420 --> 01:02:13.570
and then I have
minus something that

01:02:13.570 --> 01:02:17.250
goes like the inverse
of this excluded volume,

01:02:17.250 --> 01:02:19.760
let's write it as a.

01:02:19.760 --> 01:02:22.440
Just I write those two
parameters as a and b

01:02:22.440 --> 01:02:25.060
because I will be
taking many derivatives

01:02:25.060 --> 01:02:29.021
and I don't want to write
anything more complicated.

01:02:29.021 --> 01:02:29.520
OK.

01:02:29.520 --> 01:02:30.880
So that's the equation.

01:02:30.880 --> 01:02:35.620
We said that the location
of this critical point

01:02:35.620 --> 01:02:39.260
is obtained by the
requirement that d P by d V

01:02:39.260 --> 01:02:42.160
